    "sharqia_destinations_title": "Main Stops in Sharqia and Delta",
    "sharqia_tell_basta_title": "Tell Basta (Sharqia)",
    "sharqia_tell_basta_desc": "Considered the first point reached by the Holy Family in Egypt, and they drank from its well.",
    "sharqia_tell_basta_well_btn": "Mary's Well",
    "sharqia_tell_basta_well_txt": "Tell Basta in Zagazig city is considered one of the first stops that the Holy Family passed through after entering Egypt from the east. In this historical site, known in ancient times as 'Bubastis', it is said that the Child Jesus drank from a water spring that gushed forth by a miracle, which added special sanctity to the place.",
    "sharqia_tell_basta_site_btn": "Ancient Archaeological Area",
    "sharqia_tell_basta_site_txt": "Tell Basta today is an archaeological site that combines the ruins of ancient Egyptian civilization and the sacred memory of the Holy Family's journey.",
    "sharqia_sukha_title": "Sakha (Kafr El Sheikh)",
    "sharqia_sukha_desc": "A distinctive site where the foot of Christ left its mark on a rock.",
    "sharqia_sukha_foot_btn": "Christ's Foot",
    "sharqia_sukha_foot_txt": "The Church of Christ's Foot in Sakha in Kafr El Sheikh Governorate is considered one of the prominent sacred visitation sites for Coptic Orthodox Christians in Egypt. It is believed that the Holy Family visited this area during their flight to Egypt, and left the footprint of the Child Jesus on a stone that is still preserved inside the church to this day, and believers flock to it to seek blessings.",
    "sharqia_sukha_church_btn": "Virgin Mary Church",
    "sharqia_sukha_church_txt": "The Virgin Mary Church was built in the same area where the Holy Family stayed, and next to the church there was a baptismal site on the Roman system, after which a monastery called the Monastery of the Baptismal Site was established and remained inhabited by monks until the end of the twelfth century.",
    "sharqia_sukha_church_txt_2": "The church was restored in the eleventh century by order of the Fatimid Caliph Al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah, and in the sixteenth century, the church collapsed, and remained in ruins until Muhammad Ali Pasha ordered its reconstruction in 1846 AD while preserving its archaeological character and preserving the remaining archaeological parts of it.",
    "sharqia_mahama_title": "Al-Mahama",
    "sharqia_mahama_desc": "Where the feet of Christ the Savior extended to its good land, and the Virgin Mary sang quietly in its shade.",
    "sharqia_mahama_rest_btn": "Family's Rest",
    "sharqia_mahama_rest_txt": "It is believed that the Holy Family rested in a place near the Nile in Al-Mahama, where the village witnessed many miracles by the blessing of the presence of the Child Christ.",
    "sharqia_mahama_8baouneh_btn": "8 Baounah Celebration",
    "sharqia_mahama_8baouneh_txt": "The feast of the consecration of the church in Al-Mahama is celebrated annually on the 8th of Baounah (August). Believers flock from different regions to the Church of the Holy Family in Al-Mahama, to participate in prayers and spiritual hymns and liturgical celebrations.",
    "sharqia_belbeis_title": "Belbeis (Sharqia)",
    "sharqia_belbeis_desc": "The Belbeis area has historical roots in the Bible, as it was part of the land of Goshen where the Israelites settled.",
    "sharqia_belbeis_history_btn": "Historical Stop",
    "sharqia_belbeis_history_txt": "There are several sites in Belbeis attributed to this holy visit, including the Cave of the Virgin, where it is said that the Holy Family took refuge, and inside it there is the Church of the Virgin Mary known as the 'Cave Church'.",
    "sharqia_belbeis_churches_btn": "Ancient Churches",
    "sharqia_belbeis_churches_txt": "Belbeis city in Sharqia Governorate is considered one of the ancient Christian areas that includes a number of historical churches, some of which date back to the early centuries of Christianity in Egypt, and some are connected to the journey of the Holy Family.",
