    //History
  "history_title": "The History of the Holy Family Trail - A Blessed Journey",
  "history_section_title": "History of the Holy Family Trail",
  "history_section_subtitle": "A blessed journey through Egyptian lands",
  "history_origins_title": "Origins and reasons for the journey",
  "history_origins_p1": "The story of the Holy Family Trail dates back to the early days of the birth of Jesus Christ, when King Herod issued a decree to kill the children of Bethlehem.",
  "history_origins_p2": "In response to a divine warning, the Virgin Mary, Joseph the Carpenter, and the child Jesus left Palestine heading towards Egypt in search of safety. This arduous and long journey fulfilled Old Testament prophecies, such as 'Out of Egypt I called My Son.'",
  "history_origins_p3": "The journey extended across North Sinai, then to the Delta, reaching Upper Egypt, before the Holy Family returned to Palestine after Herod's death. During this period, the Holy Family blessed many sites and wells, leaving behind a great religious and historical legacy.",
  "history_stages_title": "Main stages of the journey",
  "history_stages_intro": "The Holy Family's journey in Egypt is divided into several main stages, each containing a group of churches, monasteries, and archaeological sites commemorating the family's passage:",
  "history_stages_sinai": "North Sinai: Entry point into Egypt, passing through cities such as Rafah, Al-Arish, and Pelusium (present-day Port Said), which were desert areas at that time.",
  "history_stages_delta": "Nile Delta: Reaching Tel Basta and Belbeis in Sharqia, then Sakha in Kafr El-Sheikh, where there are important historical monuments and relics.",
  "history_stages_cairo": "Greater Cairo: Key stations such as Ain Shams area (Mary's Tree and Matariya), and Old Cairo (Hanging Church, Abu Serga Church, Jewish Temple).",
  "history_stages_natrun": "Wadi El Natrun: Oasis of ancient monasteries where monasticism flourished after the Holy Family's passage, such as the Monastery of Anba Bishoy and the Syrian Monastery.",
  "history_stages_saeed": "Upper Egypt: Journey to Minya (Gabal El Teir) and Asyut (Al-Muharraq Monastery and Dronka Monastery), where the family resided for a long period, especially in Al-Muharraq Monastery, which is considered the heart of the trail.",
  "history_significance_title": "Spiritual and historical significance",
  "history_significance_p1": "The Holy Family Trail was not merely an escape journey, but a blessed journey that bestowed special sanctity on the Egyptian lands. This journey is seen as a symbol of safety and refuge, and evidence that Egypt has always been a land that embraces strangers and the oppressed.",
  "history_significance_p2": "Today, these sites are important religious shrines for Christians from all over the world, and also a cultural tourist destination showcasing a rich part of ancient and early Christian Egyptian history. The Egyptian government is working hard to develop the trail and present it as a global destination for pilgrimage and spiritual tourism.",
    //faq
  
  "faq_section_title": "Frequently Asked Questions",
  "faq_what_is_route_q": "What is the Holy Family Trail?",
  "faq_what_is_route_a": "The Holy Family Trail is the route taken by the Virgin Mary, Joseph the Carpenter, and the Child Jesus when they fled to Egypt to escape King Herod's persecution. The journey spans several Egyptian governorates and includes numerous archaeological and religious sites.",
  "faq_duration_q": "How long does the journey take?",
  "faq_duration_a": "The duration varies depending on the number of stops you wish to visit and your mode of transport. Day trips or multi-day itineraries can be arranged to cover the main sites in different governorates.",
  "faq_stops_q": "What are the most important stops on the trail?",
  "faq_stops_a": "Key stops include Tel Basta in Sharqia, Sakha in Kafr El-Sheikh, Wadi El-Natrun in Beheira, Old Cairo (the Hanging Church, Abu Serga Church, and the Virgin Mary’s Tree in Matariya), and areas in Minya and Assiut (Jabal al-Tayr, the Monastery of the Virgin at Al-Muharraq, and the Monastery of Dronka).",
  "faq_safety_q": "Is the trail safe for tourists?",
  "faq_safety_a": "Yes, the Egyptian government pays great attention to securing the trail and its archaeological and religious sites to ensure the safety of visitors from around the world. Always follow local guidance and travel with reputable tour operators.",
  "faq_best_time_q": "What is the best time to visit the trail?",
  "faq_best_time_a": "The best times to visit the Holy Family Trail are during autumn and spring (from October to April) when the weather is mild and ideal for tours and site exploration.",
  "faq_guide_q": "Do I need a tour guide?",
  "faq_guide_a": "It is highly recommended to hire a professional guide specialized in Coptic history and the trail to maximize your visit and learn the religious and historical stories and details of each site.",
